evaluation.response:
Here are a few small-but-showy Arduino + servo projects you can build at home. The first one includes a full parts list and code so you can get going fast.

Project 1: Sunflower Light Tracker (pan–tilt that follows a flashlight)
What it is: A cute “sunflower” head on a 2-servo pan–tilt mount that automatically turns to face the brightest light in the room. People can wave a phone flashlight and watch it smoothly track.

Why it’s great for a showcase:
- Visually charming, immediately interactive
- Only a few parts, easy to build on cardboard
- Teaches sensor fusion and servo control

Core parts:
- Arduino Uno or Nano
- 2x micro servos (SG90 or MG90S) and a simple pan–tilt bracket (or cardboard/popsicle-stick hinge build)
- 4x photoresistors (LDRs) + 4x 10 kΩ resistors
- Breadboard, jumper wires
- Separate 5 V supply for servos (at least 1–2 A), common ground with Arduino
- Cardboard for the “flower” face and a small cross-shaped baffle for the sensors
- Optional: 100–470 µF electrolytic capacitor across the servo 5 V and GND to reduce brownouts

How it works (2-axis tracking):
- Four LDRs arranged as top-left (TL), top-right (TR), bottom-left (BL), bottom-right (BR) behind a cross-shaped baffle.
- Arduino reads LDRs and computes horizontal and vertical “error” signals (which side is brighter).
- It nudges pan and tilt angles proportionally to the error until brightness is balanced.

Wiring overview:
- Each LDR forms a voltage divider with a 10 kΩ resistor:
  - One end of LDR to 5 V, the other end to an analog pin and to a 10 kΩ resistor; the other end of the resistor to GND.
  - TL -> A0, TR -> A1, BL -> A2, BR -> A3
- Servos: signal wires to D9 (pan) and D10 (tilt), power from external 5 V supply, grounds tied together with Arduino GND
- Add a large capacitor across servo 5 V and GND near the servos if you have it

Build tips:
- Mount the four LDRs close together behind a small cardboard “+” baffle so each “sees” a quadrant. This increases direction sensitivity and reduces jitter.
- Decorate the front as a sunflower face. Put the LDRs at the center.

Arduino code (drop-in):

#include <Servo.h>

Servo pan, tilt;

// Pins
const int PAN_PIN = 9;
const int TILT_PIN = 10;
const int TL_PIN = A0;
const int TR_PIN = A1;
const int BL_PIN = A2;
const int BR_PIN = A3;

// Servo state
int panAngle = 90;
int tiltAngle = 90;

// Limits (adjust to avoid mechanical binding)
const int PAN_MIN = 10, PAN_MAX = 170;
const int TILT_MIN = 20, TILT_MAX = 160;

// Control tuning
const int DEAD_BAND = 30;   // ignore small errors (ADC counts)
const float KP = 0.02;      // degrees per ADC count

// Flip directions if your servos are mounted differently
const int PAN_DIR = +1;
const int TILT_DIR = -1;

int readSmooth(int pin) {
  long sum = 0;
  for (int i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
    sum += analogRead(pin);
    delayMicroseconds(200);
  }
  return sum / 10;
}

void setup() {
  pan.attach(PAN_PIN);
  tilt.attach(TILT_PIN);
  pan.write(panAngle);
  tilt.write(tiltAngle);
}

void loop() {
  int tl = readSmooth(TL_PIN);
  int tr = readSmooth(TR_PIN);
  int bl = readSmooth(BL_PIN);
  int br = readSmooth(BR_PIN);

  // Horizontal: right minus left
  int errX = (tr + br) - (tl + bl);
  // Vertical: top minus bottom
  int errY = (tl + tr) - (bl + br);

  if (abs(errX) > DEAD_BAND) {
    panAngle += PAN_DIR * (int)(KP * errX);
  }
  if (abs(errY) > DEAD_BAND) {
    tiltAngle += TILT_DIR * (int)(KP * errY);
  }

  panAngle = constrain(panAngle, PAN_MIN, PAN_MAX);
  tiltAngle = constrain(tiltAngle, TILT_MIN, TILT_MAX);

  pan.write(panAngle);
  tilt.write(tiltAngle);

  delay(15);
}

Calibration and troubleshooting:
- If it moves the wrong way, flip PAN_DIR or TILT_DIR signs.
- Reduce jitter by increasing DEAD_BAND or adding more smoothing (more samples).
- If servos twitch when they shouldn’t, power them from a separate 5 V supply and tie grounds together.
- If motion is sluggish, increase KP slightly (e.g., 0.03); if it oscillates, decrease KP.

Showcase flair:
- Add a small buzzer “chirp” when it finds the brightest spot.
- Stick a smiley face and petals on the front; give the project a name card like “Light-Seeking Sunflower.”
- Put a small LED on the face that gets brighter as alignment improves.

Variants:
- With only 2 LDRs: do horizontal (pan) tracking only; let tilt slowly nod or sweep for personality.
- With an OLED/NeoPixel: display servo angles or a “happiness” bar when aligned.

Two other simple, cool options

2) Animatronic Eye That Follows You
- What: A big cartoon eye on a pan–tilt that looks around and blinks. Use an ultrasonic sensor (HC-SR04) to detect a viewer; it looks toward them and occasionally blinks.
- Parts: Arduino, 2 servos (pan, tilt), 1 small servo for eyelid, ultrasonic sensor, cardboard eye.
- Highlights: Very expressive; gets laughs. Program idle saccades, random blinks, and a “surprised” wide-open eyelid when someone approaches.

3) Joystick-Controlled Laserless Turret or Camera Stand
- What: A manual two-axis turret controlled by a thumb joystick. Mount a small flag, pointer, or tiny phone holder to demonstrate smooth servo control.
- Parts: Arduino, 2 servos, 1 analog joystick, optional button to toggle speed modes.
- Highlights: Dead-simple, super reliable, lets visitors drive it. You can add motion recording/playback in EEPROM for a neat “choreography” mode.

If you tell me what parts you already have (sensors, number/type of servos, power supply), I can tailor the design and code to match exactly.
